01:12.867 --> 01:15.400
THIS STORM IS ALREADY
WORSE THAN THE LAST ONE,

01:15.433 --> 01:17.267
AND WE'RE JUST
AT THE BEGINNING OF IT.

01:17.300 --> 01:21.233
Narrator: A MASSIVE ARCTIC
HURRICANE ENGULFS THE GROUNDS.

01:21.267 --> 01:25.567
Keith:
YEAH, IT'S JUST GOING TO GET
REALLY, REALLY NASTY OUT HERE.

01:25.600 --> 01:29.067
Narrator: ONE CAPTAIN PREPARES
TO FIGHT AND FISH.

01:29.067 --> 01:31.100
Keith: IF YOU GET ANYTHING DONE
WHEN YOU'RE WORKING IN A STORM,

01:31.133 --> 01:32.567
YOU'RE AHEAD OF THE FLEET

01:32.600 --> 01:35.167
BECAUSE MOST GUYS
EITHER JOG OR ANCHOR OUT.

01:37.933 --> 01:40.067
Bill: THE ARCTIC STORM --
NOTHING GOOD ABOUT IT.

01:40.100 --> 01:42.233
Narrator: ANOTHER JUST HOPES
TO RIDE IT OUT.

01:42.267 --> 01:44.767
I'D NEVER SEEN 30-FOOTERS
STACKED UP

01:44.800 --> 01:46.933
WITH A 6-SECOND INTERVAL.

01:51.433 --> 01:53.400
Johnathan: DANGEROUS OUT HERE.

01:53.433 --> 01:57.267
Narrator:
BUT MOST ARE RUNNING FOR COVER.

01:57.300 --> 02:01.300
THIS STORM IS GOING TO COST ME
A COUPLE DAYS,

02:01.333 --> 02:03.567
JUST GOT SHUT DOWN.

02:03.600 --> 02:07.367
**

02:07.400 --> 02:11.433
Jake:
HUGE STORM GOING TO BLOW 40.

02:11.467 --> 02:13.433
IT'S GOING TO BLOW 55.

02:13.467 --> 02:15.967
**

02:16.067 --> 02:18.100
I'M THREE MILES FROM ST. PAUL.

02:18.133 --> 02:21.833
I'M GETTING THE [BLEEP] [BLEEP]
KICKED OUT OF ME.

02:21.867 --> 02:23.867
ALL RIGHT, MAN, BE SAFE.
WE'LL TALK TO YOU.

02:23.900 --> 02:25.533
JUST CHECK TOMORROW, SO I'M OUT.

02:34.967 --> 02:37.833
Narrator: JUST OFF THE COAST
OF ST. PAUL ISLAND...

02:37.867 --> 02:40.300
**

02:40.333 --> 02:42.433
Nick: LOOKS LIKE WE MADE IT
JUST IN TIME.

02:42.467 --> 02:45.067
IT IS BLOWING GOOD ALREADY.

02:45.067 --> 02:47.633
I THINK IT WAS A GOOD
MOVE WE CAME IN.

02:47.667 --> 02:50.600
Narrator: ...ON THE
125-FOOT NORTHWESTERN...

02:50.633 --> 02:53.800
YEAH, THERE'S ALREADY ONE,
TWO, THREE, FOUR,

02:53.833 --> 02:56.500
FIVE, SIX, SEVEN, EIGHT, NINE.

02:56.533 --> 02:59.067
THERE'S ALREADY 10.

02:59.067 --> 03:02.100
I BET YOU'LL SEE
20, 30 BOATS HERE.

03:02.133 --> 03:04.067
Sig:
WELL, WE'RE HERE IN ST. PAUL.

03:04.100 --> 03:06.467
WE'RE RIGHT IN FRONT
OF THE HARBOR RIGHT NOW.

03:06.500 --> 03:07.933
WE'RE GOING TO ANCHOR UP.

03:07.967 --> 03:09.733
IT'S STARTING TO BLOW
PRETTY GOOD,

03:09.767 --> 03:13.467
AND IT'S SUPPOSED
TO BLOW 60 TONIGHT.

03:13.500 --> 03:17.100
Narrator: WITH A MONSTER,
450-MILE-WIDE STORM

03:17.133 --> 03:18.867
LETTING LOOSE ON
THE FISHING GROUNDS...

03:18.900 --> 03:20.233
Sig: HERE'S THE ISLAND.

03:20.267 --> 03:23.600
THE WIND IS COMING
FROM THE EAST.

03:23.633 --> 03:26.633
SO, WE'RE IN THE LEE.

03:26.667 --> 03:29.167
SO, YOU WANT TO ANCHOR UP
ANYWHERE IN HERE.

03:29.200 --> 03:33.700
Narrator:
...CAPTAIN SIG HANSEN HAS
TAKEN REFUGE BEHIND THE ISLAND.

03:33.733 --> 03:37.167
AND THEN, TONIGHT, OUT ON THE
FISHING GROUNDS WHERE WE LEFT,

03:37.200 --> 03:40.067
19 TO 33-FOOT SEAS.

03:40.067 --> 03:43.167
YOU CAN FISH IN THAT
IF YOU REALLY WANTED TO,

03:43.200 --> 03:45.100
BUT IT WOULD BE CRAZY.

03:45.133 --> 03:48.933
SO, I'M GOING TO ANCHOR UP
RIGHT OUTSIDE THE BREAK WATER.

03:48.967 --> 03:51.133
I DON'T WANT TO GO INSIDE THERE.

03:51.167 --> 03:53.133
NO, THAT'S NOT WORTH IT.

03:53.167 --> 03:55.433
Narrator: LAST SEASON...

03:55.467 --> 03:59.133
Sig: THERE'S THE ENTRANCE.
HERE WE GO.

03:59.167 --> 04:01.067
Narrator: ...SIG MADE A RUN
INTO THE HARBOR

04:01.067 --> 04:03.200
IN SIMILAR WEATHER CONDITIONS...

04:03.233 --> 04:06.267
OH [BLEEP]
WOW!

04:06.300 --> 04:08.067
UGH, COME ON, HEART.

04:08.100 --> 04:10.433
Narrator:
...NARROWLY AVOIDING DISASTER.

04:10.467 --> 04:15.500
ASK ME WOULD I DO THAT AGAIN,
THE ANSWER WOULD BE NO.

04:15.533 --> 04:16.800
WE'RE IN THE RIGHT PLACE.

04:16.833 --> 04:19.899
AT LEAST I KNOW THE GUYS
ARE SAFE AND THE BOAT IS SAFE.

04:19.933 --> 04:24.867
AND FOR ME, ESPECIALLY THIS
SEASON, THAT'S ALL THAT MATTERS.

04:24.900 --> 04:26.900
NOW ALL WE GOT TO DO
IS JUST DROP THIS ANCHOR

04:26.933 --> 04:29.100
ALONG THE SHORELINE HERE.

04:29.133 --> 04:32.067
Narrator: THE CAPTAIN WILL WAIT
FOR THE WEATHER TO DIE DOWN

04:32.100 --> 04:35.433
BEFORE OFF-LOADING HIS CRAB
AND HEADING BACK OUT.

04:35.467 --> 04:38.800
Sig: AND NO STRESS -- THAT'S
THE MOTTO FOR ME THIS YEAR.

04:38.833 --> 04:43.800
SO...PRIORITIES DIFFERENT.

04:43.833 --> 04:46.867
**

04:49.067 --> 04:51.933
WE'RE JUST TRYING
TO GET THE ANCHOR OUT.

04:51.967 --> 04:53.567
ARE THEY READY?

04:56.233 --> 04:57.900
...WAS DO YOU JUST WANT
TO TRY TO DUMP IT,

04:57.933 --> 05:00.267
OR DO YOU WANT TO TRY
TO SLOWLY EASE IT OUT?

05:00.300 --> 05:03.100
WE'RE GOING TO -- WELL, HE SAID
HE WAS GOING TO GET IT OFF,

05:03.133 --> 05:05.833
SO I DON'T KNOW
WHAT HE'S THINKING.

05:05.867 --> 05:07.167
HE THINKS HE CAN --

05:09.933 --> 05:11.900
WHERE'S EDGAR?
I WANT EDGAR UP THERE.

05:11.933 --> 05:14.633
GET EDGAR.
WHERE IS HE?

05:14.667 --> 05:17.200
Narrator:
THE ANCHOR CHAIN IS FROZEN,

05:17.233 --> 05:20.300
BUT SIG'S MIDDLE BROTHER, NORM,
HAS A PLAN --

05:20.333 --> 05:23.700
RELEASE THE BRAKE
AND LET THE WEIGHT OF THE ANCHOR

05:23.733 --> 05:25.800
FREE IT FROM THE ICE.

05:25.833 --> 05:28.900
YOU DON'T SET THE ANCHOR
WHEN IT'S BLOWING, RIGHT?

05:28.933 --> 05:31.767
LISTEN TO ME!
YOU PUT THE DOG ON!

05:31.800 --> 05:34.067
YOU ROLL IT OUT,
SO YOU KNOW YOU GOT A START!

05:34.067 --> 05:37.333
YOU ROLL IT BACK UP, TAKE
THE DOG OFF, SET THE ANCHOR!

05:37.367 --> 05:40.233
THE SKIPPER PREFERS
A DIFFERENT APPROACH --

05:40.267 --> 05:42.433
PLANT THE ANCHOR
ON DECK WITH THE DOG

05:42.467 --> 05:45.533
AND UNSPOOL THE CHAIN SLOWLY
IN SECTIONS,

05:45.567 --> 05:48.067
BREAKING THE ICE
AS THEY GO.

05:48.067 --> 05:49.833
DON'T TAKE THE DOG OFF.

05:51.567 --> 05:54.467
OH, WELL --
IT'S HAPPENING.

05:54.500 --> 05:56.500
**

05:56.533 --> 05:58.300
WE'RE GOOD, CAP.
NO, YOU'RE NOT.

05:58.333 --> 06:00.067
YOU'RE REALLY NOT GOOD.

06:00.067 --> 06:02.067
YOU GUYS ARE NOT GOOD,

06:02.100 --> 06:03.700
AND IF NORMAN CAN'T THINK
FOR HIMSELF,

06:03.733 --> 06:08.800
FIND EDGAR
OR SOMEONE THAT CAN!

06:08.833 --> 06:13.067
[ BLEEP ]

06:13.067 --> 06:16.567
I'M NEVER GOING
INTO THE WHEELHOUSE AGAIN.

06:16.600 --> 06:19.300
IF YOU GUYS WANT TO SET IT,
GO AHEAD SET IT!

06:19.333 --> 06:21.067
SEE WHAT HAPPENS!

06:21.067 --> 06:23.533
LET THE BRAKE GO!
SEE WHAT HAPPENS!

06:23.567 --> 06:26.600
**

06:34.933 --> 06:37.167
NOTHING'S
GOING TO HAPPEN.

06:45.900 --> 06:47.833
OH, THERE IT GOES.

06:47.867 --> 06:51.400
Narrator:
BROTHER NORM'S SOLUTION WORKS...

06:51.433 --> 06:54.733
WELL, I WAS WRONG
ON THAT ONE.

06:54.767 --> 06:56.300
THINK WE HOOKED.

06:56.333 --> 06:58.200
...BUT NOT WITHOUT
ADDING STRESS

06:58.233 --> 07:01.233
TO HIS ALREADY STRESSED-OUT
OLDER BROTHER.

07:01.267 --> 07:04.433
THANK YOU, LORD,
FOR THAT.

07:08.633 --> 07:11.600
I WAS GETTING PISSED.
[ SIGHS ]

07:14.767 --> 07:17.333
OH, MAN.

07:17.367 --> 07:20.333
RIGHT THERE, LIKE,
RIGHT NOW WHEN I REACHED UP

07:20.367 --> 07:24.600
AND I BREATHED IN,
IT HURTS RIGHT HERE.

07:24.633 --> 07:28.300
RIGHT THERE.

07:28.333 --> 07:30.667
OH, MAN.

07:30.700 --> 07:32.867
YEAH, THERE'S SOMETHING.

07:32.900 --> 07:35.233
IT JUST
FREAKS YOU OUT, MAN.

07:42.567 --> 07:43.900
**

07:43.933 --> 07:46.067
ON THE CRAB GROUNDS,
FACING THE BRUNT

07:46.067 --> 07:55.067
OF THE 450-MILE-WIDE ARCTIC
BLAST IS THE 155-FOOT WIZARD.

07:55.067 --> 07:58.067
**

08:00.400 --> 08:03.600
YOU NEED TO KEEP YOUR EYES
ON THE WAVES AND THE POT.

08:03.633 --> 08:06.467
ANY QUESTION WHETHER THAT WAVE
IS COMING, FORGET THE POT,

08:06.500 --> 08:09.700
GET TO THE SORTING TABLE,
HANG ON, ALL RIGHT?

08:09.733 --> 08:12.667
GOOD LUCK.
STAY SAFE.

08:12.700 --> 08:15.133
LET ME KNOW
WHEN YOU'RE READY.

08:15.167 --> 08:18.200
**

08:21.100 --> 08:24.100
Keith: I'VE GOT TO DELIVER AT
LEAST 180,000 AND 200,000 POUNDS

08:24.133 --> 08:25.967
IN LESS THAN 30 HOURS.

08:26.067 --> 08:29.067
Narrator: IN A SEASON WHERE
EFFICIENCY CAN BE THE DIFFERENCE

08:29.067 --> 08:31.733
BETWEEN FINANCIAL GAIN
OR RUIN...

08:31.767 --> 08:34.366
Keith: WE'RE TRYING
TO MINIMIZE THE COST

08:34.400 --> 08:36.567
AND MAXIMIZE THE ULTIMATE GOAL,

08:36.600 --> 08:40.500
WHICH IS TO MAKE THE MOST MONEY
PER CRAB POSSIBLE.

08:40.533 --> 08:43.299
Narrator: ...CAPTAIN
KEITH COLBURN IS HAULING GEAR

08:43.332 --> 08:47.500
IN CONDITIONS THAT MOST SKIPPERS
WOULD RUN FROM.

08:47.533 --> 08:49.500
YEAH, THE WIZARD IS A BIG BOAT.

08:49.533 --> 08:51.733
SHE DOES WELL IN BIG SEAS.

08:51.767 --> 08:54.867
THAT'S AN ADVANTAGE,
THE BOAT ITSELF.

08:54.900 --> 08:58.700
WHOO-HOO!

08:58.733 --> 09:00.800
BUT IT'S HEAVY,
AND IT LIKES TO DIP INTO WAVES.

09:00.833 --> 09:02.400
THAT'S THE ONE DOWNFALL.

09:02.433 --> 09:05.800
**

09:05.833 --> 09:08.467
WE ARE
PRETTY MUCH READY.

09:08.500 --> 09:11.633
BE SHARP.
IT'S COMING UP.

09:11.667 --> 09:14.700
**

09:20.267 --> 09:22.733
WE'D REALLY LIKE TO SEE
SOME CRAB SHOW UP,

09:22.767 --> 09:25.267
KNOCK THEM OUT,
AND GET THE HECK OUT OF HERE,

09:25.300 --> 09:27.133
ESPECIALLY WITH THE WAY
THE STORMS

09:27.167 --> 09:31.367
ARE BLOWING THROUGH HERE
RIGHT NOW.

09:31.400 --> 09:33.867
GETTING PRETTY NAUTICAL
OUT HERE, MAN!

09:33.900 --> 09:37.367
**

09:37.400 --> 09:39.600
WE'RE GOING TO FIND OUT
REAL QUICKLY

09:39.633 --> 09:42.067
IF THERE'S SOME LIFE HERE
OR NOT.

09:42.067 --> 09:45.100
**

09:49.867 --> 09:52.867
COME ON.

09:52.900 --> 09:54.467
Monte: No bueno.

09:54.500 --> 09:57.867
UGH. [ SIGHS ]

09:57.900 --> 10:01.633
**

10:01.667 --> 10:03.000
WELL, MAYBE WE'LL LUCKY

10:03.033 --> 10:05.233
AND GET A COUPLE HUNDRED COUNT
OUT OF IT.

10:05.267 --> 10:08.300
**

10:17.267 --> 10:21.500
NOT ENOUGH TO SET ON,
UNFORTUNATELY.

10:21.533 --> 10:24.233
LET'S GET THIS POT ON
BEFORE I SAY ANYTHING ELSE.

10:24.267 --> 10:25.833
COMING UP.

10:25.867 --> 10:29.567
**

10:29.600 --> 10:32.533
NICE, SOLID 30-FOOT SEAS
OUT HERE RIGHT NOW.

10:32.567 --> 10:35.600
**

10:39.767 --> 10:40.933
[ SIGHS ]

10:40.967 --> 10:44.533
**

10:44.567 --> 10:47.800
COME ON, BABY.
COME BACK AROUND.

10:47.833 --> 10:50.633
AH, DAMN, DUDE.

10:50.667 --> 10:53.400
OKAY, THAT ONE
DOESN'T LOOK GOOD.

10:53.433 --> 10:56.267
**

10:56.300 --> 10:59.267
PULLING NOTHING, REALLY.

10:59.300 --> 11:01.500
**

11:01.533 --> 11:03.300
EIGHT FIVE.

11:03.333 --> 11:06.300
I WAS HOPING THAT POT
HAVE SOME BETTER NUMBERS IN IT

11:06.333 --> 11:09.900
SO I COULD RUN THIS STRING BACK
THROUGH THIS SPOT HERE.

11:09.933 --> 11:12.967
**

11:15.533 --> 11:16.767
YOU KNOW WHAT?

11:16.800 --> 11:19.433
THIS IS NOT GOING TO
FINISH THE TRIP FOR US HERE.

11:19.467 --> 11:22.333
I'M COMMITTING TO A MOVE --

11:22.367 --> 11:26.967
HEAD NORTH, GO THROUGH
ALL THE GEAR UP THERE.

11:27.067 --> 11:29.700
Narrator: HAULING LOW NUMBERS...

11:29.733 --> 11:32.133
Keith: PROBABLY STACK
A DECKLOAD ON HERE,

11:32.167 --> 11:33.567
MAYBE MOVE THEM UP
THE HILL A WAYS,

11:33.600 --> 11:34.833
SEE WHAT WE CAN FIND.

11:34.867 --> 11:37.433
Narrator: ...KEITH HEADS
INTO THE HEART OF THE STORM,

11:37.467 --> 11:40.133
SEARCHING FOR THE ELUSIVE CRAB.

11:40.167 --> 11:43.200
**

11:52.833 --> 11:56.400
OH, COME ON.
BIG WAVE ON THE PORTSIDE, GUYS.

11:56.433 --> 11:58.633
-HEY, HEADS UP! HEADS UP!
-MAYBE NEXT YEAR.

12:04.467 --> 12:07.300
WATCH YOUR HOLE!

12:07.333 --> 12:09.733
OH, BOY.

12:09.767 --> 12:13.300
**

12:13.333 --> 12:15.600
HEADS UP!
HEADS UP!

12:15.633 --> 12:20.800
**

12:20.833 --> 12:23.500
NO. NO. NO.
THAT ONE DOESN'T LOOK GOOD.

12:25.767 --> 12:27.467
OKAY, GUYS, WE MIGHT
TAKE A LITTLE DRINK.

12:27.500 --> 12:29.733
HANG ON! HANG ON!
HANG ON, EVERYBODY! HANG ON!

12:38.067 --> 12:42.067
Narrator: ON THE WIZARD...

12:42.067 --> 12:45.633
NO. NO. NO.
THAT ONE DOESN'T LOOK GOOD.

12:48.167 --> 12:49.767
OKAY, GUYS, WE MIGHT
TAKE A LITTLE DRINK.

12:49.800 --> 12:52.067
HANG ON! HANG ON!
HANG ON, EVERYBODY! HANG ON!

12:52.100 --> 12:55.133
**

13:02.867 --> 13:06.567
YOU OKAY?
EVERYBODY OKAY?

13:13.967 --> 13:16.433
[ BLEEP ]

13:16.467 --> 13:19.500
**

13:22.800 --> 13:24.700
THERE'S NOTHING WORSE
THAN A 30-FOOT WAVE

13:24.733 --> 13:26.133
THAT TURNS INTO A 40-FOOTER

13:26.167 --> 13:29.267
WITH A BUNCH OF GREEN TEETH
ON IT ALL OF A SUDDEN.

13:29.300 --> 13:32.900
Man: WELL, THIS IS THE WORST
WE'VE SEEN SO FAR ALREADY,

13:32.933 --> 13:36.967
AND IT'S ONLY GOING
TO GET WORSE.

13:37.067 --> 13:40.467
Narrator: DESPITE
TREACHEROUS CONDITIONS...

13:40.500 --> 13:43.433
Keith: DOESN'T MATTER IF YOU'RE
ANCHORED UP BEHIND ST. PAUL,

13:43.467 --> 13:45.200
WE'RE WORKING IN THE STORM.

13:45.233 --> 13:46.667
THERE'S RISKS INVOLVED IN THIS.

13:46.700 --> 13:49.633
Narrator: ...THE VETERAN SKIPPER
DOES NOT WAVER.

13:49.667 --> 13:52.700
Keith: BUT YOU KNOW, THERE'S GOT
TO BE SOME REWARD FOR RISK.

13:52.733 --> 13:55.667
LET'S SEE IF WE CAN
MAKE THIS WORK.

13:55.700 --> 13:57.800
WE JUST NEED TO FIND THE CRAB.

14:02.500 --> 14:05.367
Narrator: 80 MILES NORTHEAST...

14:11.233 --> 14:13.067
...ON THE 107-FOOT SAGA...

14:13.100 --> 14:16.533
Jake: ST. PAUL'S A VERY
DIFFICULT HARBOR.

14:16.567 --> 14:19.667
YOU GET ONE WAY IN,
AND ONCE YOU START GOING IN,

14:19.700 --> 14:20.933
YOU CAN'T TURN AROUND,

14:20.967 --> 14:22.700
YOU GOT TO JUST
KEEP GOING THROUGH.

14:22.733 --> 14:24.833
SO, NOW THESE GUYS
GOT TO DO SOMETHING

14:24.867 --> 14:26.733
THAT NONE OF THEM
HAVE EVER DONE,

14:26.767 --> 14:30.500
WHICH IS SET THE ANCHOR
IN ROUGH WEATHER ON THIS BOAT.

14:30.533 --> 14:33.867
**

14:33.900 --> 14:37.067
Narrator: ...LIKE THE OTHER
10 BOATS OFF ST. PAUL ISLAND...

14:37.100 --> 14:39.200
COME ON.
I'LL TRY TO GET HER TURNED.

14:39.233 --> 14:41.267
Narrator: ...CAPTAIN
JAKE ANDERSON AND HIS CREW

14:41.300 --> 14:44.267
ARE ANCHORING UP
WHILE WAITING OUT THE STORM.

14:44.300 --> 14:47.333
**

14:56.333 --> 15:00.233
Narrator:
AND THEY'RE DOING IT WITHOUT
THE HELP OF DEAN GRIBBLE,

15:00.267 --> 15:02.167
JAKE'S MOST SENIOR DECKHAND.

15:02.200 --> 15:04.067
Jake:
JUST GO TO YOUR ROOM, DUDE.

15:04.100 --> 15:07.167
I CAN'T DEAL WITH YOU ANYMORE.
I'M SORRY.

15:12.067 --> 15:14.067
HE KEEPS COMING UP HERE
WHEN I'VE GOT

15:14.067 --> 15:16.200
MILLIONS OF THINGS
GOING ON,

15:16.233 --> 15:18.633
AND HE KEEPS TRYING
TO MAKE HIMSELF IMPORTANT.

15:18.667 --> 15:22.367
HE WANTS TO BE THE ONE,
AND I DON'T HAVE TIME FOR THAT.

15:22.400 --> 15:25.100
I'VE GOT OTHER [BLEEP]

15:25.133 --> 15:27.367
Narrator:
JUST 12 HOURS AGO...

15:27.400 --> 15:28.700
GET OUT
OF MY WHEELHOUSE.

15:28.733 --> 15:30.467
WE'RE FINALLY ON
SOME [BLEEP] BANGERS.

15:30.500 --> 15:31.633
GET OUT OF MY FACE!

15:31.667 --> 15:32.867
IF YOU DON'T GET OUT
OF MY WHEELHOUSE,

15:32.900 --> 15:35.067
I'LL CALL THE COAST GUARD,
AND I'LL HAVE YOU ARRESTED.

15:35.100 --> 15:37.267
...JAKE FIRED DEAN,

15:37.300 --> 15:41.233
KEEPING HIM OFF THE DECK
UNTIL THEY REACH PORT.

15:44.067 --> 15:45.833
BE A WASTE.
AND THESE GUYS TO GO FISHING

15:45.867 --> 15:48.333
WITH FOUR GUYS FOR OPIE SEASON

15:48.367 --> 15:51.567
WITHOUT THREE [BLEEP] MINUTES
OF EXPERIENCE OUT THERE.

15:51.600 --> 15:54.233
BUT WHATEVER.

15:54.267 --> 15:56.067
GO AHEAD LET IT OUT,
DAVE.

15:56.067 --> 15:59.100
**

16:02.167 --> 16:05.067
KEEP LETTING IT OUT.

16:05.100 --> 16:08.333
GRAB IT. NOT TOO FAST.
NOT TOO FAST.

16:08.367 --> 16:11.167
SHE GRABBED.
SHE'S GRABBING.

16:11.200 --> 16:13.833
ALL RIGHT, YEAH,
THAT'LL WORK.

16:13.867 --> 16:15.700
MAKE SURE YOU DOG IT.

16:15.733 --> 16:18.867
Narrator: TO FINISH THE JOB,
THE DRUM MUST BE DOGGED,

16:18.900 --> 16:20.467
OR CLAMPED, IN PLACE.

16:22.867 --> 16:27.433
HOLD IT FROM RESPOOLING OUT.

16:27.467 --> 16:29.700
IS THERE A DOG
ON THERE, DAVE?

16:29.733 --> 16:32.900
**

16:32.933 --> 16:36.767
OKAY, GO AHEAD
AND GO DOWN AND GET ONE DUG.

16:36.800 --> 16:41.233
**

16:41.267 --> 16:43.067
WE'RE HOOKED UP.

16:43.067 --> 16:45.667
I GOT TO STILL WATCH IT,
THOUGH.

16:45.700 --> 16:48.733
**

16:53.567 --> 16:56.833
Narrator: WHILE THE STORM
CONTINUES TO INTENSIFY...

16:56.867 --> 16:59.267
**

16:59.300 --> 17:02.500
Jake: I'M NERVOUS.
I DON'T LIKE BEING IN ST. PAUL.

17:02.533 --> 17:05.067
IT'S A PRETTY SERIOUS DEAL.

17:05.099 --> 17:09.500
Narrator:
...THE YOUNG SKIPPER MAKES SURE
HIS GREEN CREW IS SQUARED AWAY.

17:09.532 --> 17:11.333
Jake: JUST BE RACE-READY.

17:11.367 --> 17:13.067
DON'T BE THINKING WE'RE GOING TO
GO TO OUR RACKS,

17:13.067 --> 17:16.400
YOU KNOW, HANG OUT, BECAUSE
IT DOESN'T WORK LIKE THAT.

17:16.433 --> 17:20.633
**

17:20.666 --> 17:22.700
[ METAL CREAKING ]

17:26.200 --> 17:28.067
I MEAN, MOST OF US
ARE NEW HERE TOGETHER,

17:28.067 --> 17:30.967
SO EVERYBODY CAN'T BE EXPECTING
THE NEXT GUY TO COVER THEIR ASS.

17:31.067 --> 17:34.567
EVERYBODY HAS GOT TO GET UP
AND GO AND BE READY TO JAM.

17:34.600 --> 17:38.467
**

17:38.500 --> 17:39.967
-HEY, JAKE!
-JAKE!

17:41.267 --> 17:43.767
YEP!

17:43.800 --> 17:46.467
**

17:46.500 --> 17:50.667
[ BLEEP ]

17:50.700 --> 17:53.300
Narrator: DURING WHEEL WATCH,

17:53.333 --> 17:57.867
HANNES HUSWICK NOTICES
THAT THE SAGA IS MOVING.

17:57.900 --> 17:59.833
Jake:
I NEED SOMEBODY OUT THERE QUICK.

17:59.867 --> 18:02.867
I DON'T THINK WE HAVE
OUR ANCHOR ON.

18:02.900 --> 18:06.600
Narrator:
THE ONE-TON ANCHOR IS NO LONGER
HOLDING THE BOAT IN PLACE.

18:17.133 --> 18:19.067
[ BLEEPING ]

18:22.900 --> 18:26.300
WE LOST THE ANCHOR...

18:26.333 --> 18:28.333
AGAIN.

18:31.200 --> 18:33.067
THE CABLE IS COMPLETELY OUT.

18:39.167 --> 18:41.100
THAT'S WHY I TOLD YOU GUYS
TO PUT A [BLEEP] DOG

18:41.133 --> 18:43.300
ON THAT [BLEEP], SOMETHING!

18:43.333 --> 18:52.467
**

18:52.500 --> 18:54.533
YEAH.

18:54.567 --> 18:56.800
NEED SOME EXPERIENCE
ON THIS BOAT, I GUESS.

19:01.333 --> 19:03.500
WE JUST [BLEEP] JOG.

19:03.533 --> 19:07.067
THIS 60-KNOT WIND IS VERY,
VERY DANGEROUS.

19:07.067 --> 19:10.267
Narrator:
NO LONGER MOORED, THE YOUNG
SKIPPER WILL SPEND THE NIGHT

19:10.300 --> 19:13.133
TRYING TO KEEP THE SAGA
OFF THE ROCKS.

19:13.167 --> 19:15.800
Jake:
CANNOT LEAVE THIS WHEELHOUSE.

19:15.833 --> 19:17.133
AS SOON AS I LEAVE
THIS WHEELHOUSE,

19:17.167 --> 19:18.833
ALL HELL BREAKS LOOSE.

19:18.867 --> 19:21.867
**

19:28.867 --> 19:31.833
**

19:31.867 --> 19:35.933
Narrator: 290 MILES
NORTHWEST OF DUTCH HARBOR...

19:35.967 --> 19:38.067
Keith: WE'RE GOING TO
GET BEAT UP OUT HERE.

19:38.100 --> 19:40.500
WE'RE IN A BIG [BLEEP] STORM.

19:40.533 --> 19:42.733
Narrator: ...IN THE HEART
OF THE ARCTIC HURRICANE...

19:42.767 --> 19:44.233
Keith:
WELL, AT THIS POINT NOW,

19:44.267 --> 19:46.067
NOW WE GOT
TWO REAL IMPORTANT REASONS

19:46.067 --> 19:47.200
TO GET THIS GEAR IN THE WATER.

19:47.233 --> 19:48.267
ONE, IT'S NOT FISHING.

19:48.300 --> 19:50.500
BUT TWO, THE STACK'S
A SAFETY ISSUE.

19:50.533 --> 19:53.933
Narrator: ...THE DANGEROUS
100,000-POUND STACK

19:53.967 --> 19:55.200
WEIGHING DOWN THE WIZARD...

19:55.233 --> 19:58.233
IT'S THE NORTH CORNER
OF WHERE WE SET.

19:58.267 --> 20:00.533
WE NEED TO SEE
IF THERE'S ANY CRAB THERE.

20:00.567 --> 20:04.033
HOPING IN TWO SPOT CHECKS,
WE'LL HAVE ENOUGH INFORMATION.

20:04.067 --> 20:06.233
Narrator: ...CAPTAIN
KEITH COLBURN IS BANKING ON

20:06.267 --> 20:11.067
SOME PROSPECT POTS PAYING OFF SO
HE CAN LIGHTEN HIS BOAT'S LOAD.

20:11.100 --> 20:13.100
Keith: WELL, NOT REALLY
THE OPTIMUM CONDITIONS

20:13.133 --> 20:15.700
FOR TRYING TO HAUL A CRAB POT,

20:15.733 --> 20:17.700
BUT WE'RE JUST GOING
TO BE REAL SAFE,

20:17.733 --> 20:20.200
MINIMIZE THE AMOUNT OF TIME
YOU HAVE ON DECK.

20:20.233 --> 20:23.200
THIS IS LIKE PIT-CREW FISHING
RIGHT HERE.

20:23.233 --> 20:27.100
Narrator: TO LIMIT EXPOSURE
TO THE HARSH 30-FOOT SEAS...

20:27.133 --> 20:29.267
HERE COMES THE CAR -- BOOM --
INTO THE PITS.

20:29.300 --> 20:34.033
BANG, CRAB, BLOCK, CRANE,
POT BACK IN THE WATER.

20:34.067 --> 20:38.033
Narrator: ...THE CREW WILL HAUL
A POT AND THEN HIDE OFF-DECK

20:38.067 --> 20:40.700
UNTIL THE CAPTAIN STEAMS
TO THE NEXT ONE.

20:40.733 --> 20:44.200
**

20:44.233 --> 20:46.233
YOU KNOW, I THINK
I JUST FOUND MY POT.

20:46.267 --> 20:48.133
[ PHONE RINGS ]

20:48.167 --> 20:49.533
YEAH?

20:52.333 --> 20:54.100
YEAH, GO ON OUT.

20:57.533 --> 21:00.767
LET'S GO ON DECK.

21:00.800 --> 21:03.833
**

21:05.800 --> 21:07.633
OKAY, LET'S DO THIS, GUYS.

21:07.667 --> 21:09.667
ON AND OFF
AS QUICK AS POSSIBLE.

21:09.700 --> 21:12.733
**

21:17.767 --> 21:20.433
COME ON.
BE SOMETHING.

21:20.467 --> 21:23.500
**

21:27.933 --> 21:30.567
-GOT IT!
-COME ON, CRAB.

21:30.600 --> 21:33.733
A COUPLE HUNDRED, MAN.
JUST A COUPLE HUNDRED.

21:33.767 --> 21:36.800
**

21:40.467 --> 21:42.133
WHOO!

21:42.167 --> 21:43.900
WELL, THERE'S A CRAB DANCE.

21:43.933 --> 21:46.967
**

21:50.067 --> 21:52.167
JUST LIKE A STOCK-CAR RACE,
TEAM, AS QUICK AS YOU CAN,

21:52.200 --> 21:54.967
GET IT ON AND OFF.

21:55.067 --> 21:59.367
OKAY, GUYS, ON AND OFF.
ON AND OFF.

21:59.400 --> 22:01.233
COME ON. COME ON. COME ON.

22:01.267 --> 22:04.667
**

22:04.700 --> 22:06.700
GET RID
OF THAT [BLEEP] THING.

22:06.733 --> 22:08.967
[ ALL CHEERING ]

22:09.067 --> 22:10.333
COME ON!

22:10.367 --> 22:12.267
WE'RE GOING TO JUST
TALLY IT UP INSIDE, OKAY?

22:12.300 --> 22:13.633
COME ON, GUYS.

22:13.667 --> 22:16.700
**

22:21.367 --> 22:25.567
[ DOOR LATCHES ]
THAT CLUNK IS MUSIC TO MY EARS.

22:25.600 --> 22:28.067
THAT MEANS THE CREW
IS BACK INSIDE AND SAFE.

22:28.100 --> 22:29.833
ROGER. YEAH.

22:29.867 --> 22:32.100
Monte: Got 260.

22:32.133 --> 22:33.500
260?

22:33.533 --> 22:36.933
RIGHT ON.
GO ON OUT.

22:36.967 --> 22:39.533
260 CRAB IN 21 HOURS.

22:39.567 --> 22:41.600
WE MAY BE ON TO SOMETHING.

22:41.633 --> 22:44.667
**

22:50.100 --> 22:52.300
RIGHT ON. NICE TOSS.

23:01.333 --> 23:02.733
LET'S SEE.
WHAT DO WE GOT HERE?

23:02.767 --> 23:04.433
COME ON.
GIVE ME A POT OF CRAB.

23:04.467 --> 23:07.333
OH, IT'S GOT SOMETHING IN IT.
NOT SURE WHAT.

23:07.367 --> 23:09.433
YEAH, SHAKE THE HELL OUT OF IT
AND BEAT IT UP GOOD.

23:09.467 --> 23:11.467
LET'S GET IT
RIGHT BACK OVER THE SIDE.

23:11.500 --> 23:13.400
LET'S PUT HER OUT, GUYS.
WIPE HER OUT.

23:13.433 --> 23:17.633
**

23:17.667 --> 23:19.067
-THANK YOU.
-YEAH, BABY!

23:19.067 --> 23:20.500
-LET'S GO!
-HERE WE GO!

23:20.533 --> 23:22.533
AS SOON AS IT'S READY,
YOU CAN DUMP IT.

23:22.567 --> 23:25.600
**

23:30.500 --> 23:32.533
JUST STAY SHARP, GUYS.
STAY SHARP.

23:32.567 --> 23:35.600
**

23:38.833 --> 23:41.233
[ PHONE RINGS ]
YEAH?

23:41.267 --> 23:44.100
So, that was
a real nice crab -- 320.

23:44.133 --> 23:45.867
We can work on that.

23:45.900 --> 23:47.733
Hey, I'm just going to
make my turn,

23:47.767 --> 23:49.767
SO HAVE EVERYBODY
GET OUT ON DECK

23:49.800 --> 23:51.400
up under
the shelter wall.

23:51.433 --> 23:52.833
ALL RIGHT.

23:52.867 --> 23:54.800
SOON AS I COME AROUND,
I'LL GO FOR IT.

23:54.833 --> 23:58.267
YOU GUYS START
DUMPING RIGHT AWAY, OKAY?

23:58.300 --> 24:00.100
Narrator:
NOW THAT HE'S FOUND THE CRAB...

24:00.133 --> 24:01.500
THE WEATHER IS GOING
TO BE OFF THE GUYS.

24:01.533 --> 24:02.967
THAT'S
THE IMPORTANT THING.

24:03.067 --> 24:05.567
...THE VETERAN SKIPPER WILL
LAY OUT A STRING IN A DIRECTION

24:05.600 --> 24:09.367
THAT PROTECTS HIS CREW
FROM THE BRUNT OF THE STORM.

24:09.400 --> 24:11.167
SOON AS IT'S READY,
LET HER FLY.

24:11.200 --> 24:12.767
WE'VE GOT FISHING HERE.

24:12.800 --> 24:14.767
NOW WE JUST NEED TO GET
THE GEAR FISHING.

24:14.800 --> 24:17.667
**

24:17.700 --> 24:19.733
YEAH, WE'RE ONLY GOING TO GET
THROUGH THIS GEAR ONE TIME.

24:19.767 --> 24:20.933
THAT'S IT.

24:20.967 --> 24:22.333
WE'RE GOING TO GET
THROUGH IT ONE TIME,

24:22.367 --> 24:24.533
AND THEN IT'S TIME
TO GO IN AND DELIVER.

24:24.567 --> 24:26.767
SO, WE GOT TO MAKE IT
A REAL GOOD ONE.

24:26.800 --> 24:29.733
WE REALLY NEED THIS STORM
SET TO PAY OFF.

24:29.767 --> 24:32.800
**

24:37.067 --> 24:43.967
Narrator: 85 MILES NORTHEAST
IN ST. PAUL HARBOR...

24:44.067 --> 24:45.900
I'M GOING TO GO
TO THE NORTH DOCK.

24:45.933 --> 24:48.800
THAT'S ALL THE WAY DOWN THERE.

24:48.833 --> 24:50.167
Narrator:
...ON THE NORTHWESTERN...

24:50.200 --> 24:52.133
ON THE PORTSIDE?

24:52.167 --> 24:55.800
IT'S GOING TO HAVE TO BE,
BECAUSE I MAY GO TO THE DOCTOR

24:55.833 --> 24:58.100
FOR A CHECKUP ANYWAY.

24:58.133 --> 24:59.167
YEAH.

24:59.200 --> 25:02.233
-HEY, PORTSIDE!
-PORTSIDE!

25:02.267 --> 25:04.733
Narrator: ...CAPTAIN SIG HANSEN
HAS TAKEN ADVANTAGE

25:04.767 --> 25:08.600
OF A LULL IN THE STORM
TO OFF-LOAD HIS CRAB

25:08.633 --> 25:13.167
AND CHECK ON SOME UNSETTLING
ISSUES WITH HIS HEART.

25:13.200 --> 25:15.533
YEAH, I DON'T KNOW
WHY MY SIDE IS BURNING.

25:15.567 --> 25:18.600
**

25:27.667 --> 25:31.233
I FEEL THAT PAIN RIGHT NOW.
YOU KNOW WHAT I MEAN?

25:31.267 --> 25:32.567
JUST HARD TO GO THERE AND SAY

25:32.600 --> 25:35.667
THAT YOU GOT THIS
ON AND OFF AGAIN.

25:35.700 --> 25:38.233
YOU KNOW WHAT I'M SAYING?

25:38.267 --> 25:41.167
I JUST -- I DON'T KNOW.

25:41.200 --> 25:43.367
JUST DON'T KNOW
WHAT IT IS, DUDE.

25:43.400 --> 25:46.433
**

25:49.867 --> 25:52.433
SIG, WE'RE ALWAYS WORRIED
ABOUT HIS HEALTH RIGHT NOW

25:52.467 --> 25:56.433
BECAUSE OF LAST YEAR,
AND WE'RE WATCHING HIM.

25:56.467 --> 25:58.633
SEE WHAT HAPPENS.

25:58.667 --> 26:00.233
HE'S STRUGGLING.

26:00.267 --> 26:03.467
**

26:03.500 --> 26:05.333
I GOT TO GET OUT OF HERE.

26:18.133 --> 26:24.467
Narrator: JUST OUTSIDE
THE HARBOR ON THE SAGA...

26:24.500 --> 26:26.367
[ YAWNS ]

26:26.400 --> 26:29.867
WELL, LAST NIGHT SUCKED.

26:29.900 --> 26:35.067
WE LOST OUR ANCHOR, PUTTING
THE BOAT AT RISK IN THE HARBOR.

26:35.067 --> 26:37.300
Narrator: ...WITHOUT HIS ANCHOR,
CAPTAIN JAKE ANDERSON

26:37.333 --> 26:41.233
WAS FORCED TO SPEND THE NIGHT
JOGGING IN TURBULENT SEAS.

26:41.267 --> 26:44.233
Jake: SO, IF I'M GOING TO MUCK
AND ANCHOR UP,

26:44.267 --> 26:47.067
I GOT TO DO IT RIGHT NOW.

26:47.067 --> 26:49.567
FOR AN EXPERIENCED CREW
AND CAPTAIN,

26:49.600 --> 26:51.567
IT'S A PRETTY
STANDARD PROCEDURE,

26:51.600 --> 26:56.933
BUT WITH A GREEN CREW,
IT CAN GO WRONG REAL QUICK.

26:56.967 --> 26:59.333
Narrator:
TO RETRIEVE THE ANCHOR,

26:59.367 --> 27:02.733
THE CREW MUST HAUL
THE LOOSE STEEL AND CHAIN,

27:02.767 --> 27:06.567
USING THE CRANE
TO HOIST IT UP IN SECTIONS.

27:06.600 --> 27:10.500
IF INCORRECTLY FASTENED,
A ONE-TON WRECKING BALL

27:10.533 --> 27:12.933
WILL BE SENT
ON A PATH OF DESTRUCTION.

27:12.967 --> 27:16.800
**

27:16.833 --> 27:21.300
IT'S BROKEN BONES,
BROKEN BODIES, PEOPLE DIE.

27:21.333 --> 27:22.900
I DON'T KNOW IF THESE GUYS KNOW

27:22.933 --> 27:26.067
WHAT THEY'RE UP AGAINST
RIGHT NOW.

27:26.100 --> 27:28.300
DEAN IS THE ONLY ONE
THAT'S EVER MUCKED AN ANCHOR UP.

27:28.333 --> 27:31.167
Narrator: FOR THE SAFETY
OF HIS GREEN CREW...

27:33.233 --> 27:36.733
...JAKE CALLS ON THE ONLY HAND
WHO CAN DO THE JOB,

27:36.767 --> 27:39.600
THE MAN HE FIRED.

27:39.633 --> 27:42.067
I'M GOING TO NEED YOUR HELP
ON THIS ONE.

27:42.067 --> 27:44.800
SURE.

27:44.833 --> 27:47.167
I HAVE TO
MUCK THIS ANCHOR UP.

27:47.200 --> 27:50.167
**

27:50.200 --> 27:51.400
ALL RIGHT, YEAH,
JUST GIVE ME A MINUTE.

27:51.433 --> 27:55.267
IT'LL BE FINE.

27:55.300 --> 27:57.467
THIS IS JUST ME
THAT NEEDS SOMEONE

27:57.500 --> 28:00.133
WHO HAS EXPERIENCE
WITH THIS.

28:00.167 --> 28:03.200
**

28:14.167 --> 28:17.167
WE'RE AT THE BUOYS
TO THE ANCHOR,

28:17.200 --> 28:20.300
SO IT'S REALLY HARD
TO GET THAT ALL THE WAY UP.

28:20.333 --> 28:22.533
IT'S GOING TO BE A TOUGH SHOT.

28:22.567 --> 28:24.300
IT'S NOT LIKE A TRAILER ON IT,

28:24.333 --> 28:26.300
SO THERE'S NO LINE
DRAPED ACROSS.

28:26.333 --> 28:28.267
IT'S JUST A LINE
GOING STRAIGHT DOWN.

28:28.300 --> 28:31.067
**

28:31.067 --> 28:35.433
OKAY, DEAN. GAME ON.

28:35.467 --> 28:38.500
**

28:40.067 --> 28:41.733
HERE YOU GO.
COMING UP.

28:41.767 --> 28:44.800
**

28:48.700 --> 28:50.500
HOLD ON.
BE CAREFUL.

28:50.533 --> 28:54.167
**

28:54.200 --> 28:55.733
GOING UP! EASY!

28:55.767 --> 29:00.133
Dean: UP! PULL IT UP
AS MUCH AS WE CAN!

29:00.167 --> 29:03.800
Jake:
GUYS, DON'T GO TOO FAR OUT.

29:03.833 --> 29:05.267
HOLD ON.

29:05.300 --> 29:08.533
SOMEBODY GET A CHOKER
ON THE CHAIN.

29:08.567 --> 29:11.967
ALL RIGHT, NOW JUST COME OUT
JUST A LITTLE BIT!

29:12.067 --> 29:13.600
UP!
YEP!

29:13.633 --> 29:15.567
CARRY THAT DOWN!

29:15.600 --> 29:18.067
THAT'S FINE!
THAT IS FINE! IT WORKS!

29:18.100 --> 29:21.133
HEY, PULL THAT CHAIN IN!
PULL IT IN!

29:21.167 --> 29:25.233
GUYS, THAT'S GOOD.
THAT'S GOOD.

29:25.267 --> 29:28.367
I'M ACTUALLY PRETTY PROUD
OF MY GUYS.

29:28.400 --> 29:29.833
THEY'RE DOING IT,

29:29.867 --> 29:33.433
AND THEY'RE DOING
A PRETTY GOOD JOB OF BEING SAFE.

29:33.467 --> 29:36.067
THERE SHE IS.

29:36.067 --> 29:40.100
FANTASTIC JOB, GUYS.
FANTASTIC JOB.

29:40.133 --> 29:41.567
THAT'S WHY I'M HERE.

29:41.600 --> 29:43.933
Narrator: WITH THE ANCHOR
AND CHAIN ONBOARD...

29:43.967 --> 29:46.967
SECURITY, SECURITY, THIS IS
FISHING BOAT SAGA

29:47.067 --> 29:48.767
HEADING INBOUND TO ST. PAUL.

29:48.800 --> 29:51.167
MAN:
Saga, you're good to go there.

29:51.200 --> 29:55.267
Narrator: ...THE CAPTAIN TURNS
THE BOAT TOWARDS ST. PAUL.

29:55.300 --> 29:58.633
Jake: DEAN, HE'S A GOOD HAND.

29:58.667 --> 30:01.133
YOU CAN SEE RIGHT THERE,
DEAN CAN --

30:01.167 --> 30:05.900
THERE'S NOTHING ON THIS BOAT
THAT DEAN IS AFRAID OF DOING.

30:05.933 --> 30:08.033
AS MUCH AS HE PISSED ME OFF,
AS MUCH AS HE CROSSED

30:08.067 --> 30:11.000
MY BOUNDARIES, FOR ME,
IT'S REALLY SAD.

30:11.033 --> 30:13.233
I FEEL BAD FOR DEAN.

30:13.267 --> 30:15.433
I DON'T KNOW WHAT TO DO NOW.

30:17.600 --> 30:20.167
**

30:20.200 --> 30:23.500
Narrator: ACROSS THE ISLAND...

30:23.533 --> 30:25.500
Sig:
I WANT TO GO TO THE CLINIC HERE

30:25.533 --> 30:27.367
BECAUSE I DON'T KNOW WHAT IT IS,
BUT I HAVE THIS --

30:27.400 --> 30:33.333
IT'S A PAIN, LIKE, RIGHT
IN MY CHEST ON MY LEFT SIDE.

30:33.367 --> 30:36.467
Narrator: ...WITH HIS CREW
OFF-LOADING, CAPTAIN SIG HANSEN

30:36.500 --> 30:39.600
TURNS HIS ATTENTION
TO A MORE PRESSING MATTER,

30:39.633 --> 30:41.500
HIS HEALTH.

30:41.533 --> 30:44.600
LAST TIME, I DIDN'T THINK
IT WAS ANYTHING,

30:44.633 --> 30:47.700
AND [laughing]
IT WAS A HEART ATTACK,

30:47.733 --> 30:51.167
SO THAT'S WHAT GOT ME
ALL FREAKED OUT.

30:51.200 --> 30:54.633
Narrator: ONLY A YEAR REMOVED
FROM A NEAR-DEATH EXPERIENCE,

30:54.667 --> 30:57.767
THE SKIPPER ISN'T
TAKING ANY CHANCES.

30:57.800 --> 31:00.433
IT'S NO FUN BECAUSE
YOU'RE ALWAYS THINKING ABOUT IT

31:00.467 --> 31:01.733
IN THE BACK OF YOUR MIND,

31:01.767 --> 31:05.300
AND THAT'S WHAT BOTHERS ME
EVERY DAY.

31:05.333 --> 31:07.800
THIS IS LIKE A MIND TRIP.
THAT'S WHAT IT IS.

31:07.833 --> 31:09.800
I'M FEELING I'M A MENTAL
BASKET CASE RIGHT NOW,

31:09.833 --> 31:12.400
AND THAT'S NOT HOW
I SHOULD BE FEELING.

31:12.433 --> 31:15.100
WE'LL GO IN THERE
AND SEE WHAT THEY SAY.

31:15.133 --> 31:18.167
**

31:29.067 --> 31:30.800
Narrator: BACK AT DOCK...

31:30.833 --> 31:34.567
**

31:34.600 --> 31:38.600
JUST WAITING ON SIG
TO GET BACK FROM THE CLINIC.

31:38.633 --> 31:40.167
BEEN THERE A WHILE.

31:40.200 --> 31:43.400
I DON'T KNOW WHAT'S TAKING
SO LONG,

31:43.433 --> 31:48.433
BUT FIGURED I'D GO OVER,
PAY JAKE A VISIT.

31:48.467 --> 31:49.733
HOW'S IT GOING?

31:49.767 --> 31:51.533
Narrator:
...EDGAR CHECKS IN WITH FORMER

31:51.567 --> 31:55.200
NORTHWESTERN DECKHAND
JAKE ANDERSON.

31:55.233 --> 31:57.200
WHY IS IT ALL PURPLE
IN HERE?

31:57.233 --> 31:59.600
SHEER BOREDOM.

31:59.633 --> 32:01.800
[ IMITATES CLUB MUSIC ]

32:01.833 --> 32:03.500
IT'S BECAUSE AT NIGHT,
YOU CAN PUT THEM ON,

32:03.533 --> 32:06.233
AND YOU CAN SEE
IN HERE STILL,

32:06.267 --> 32:07.733
BUT IT DOESN'T
[BLEEP] UP YOUR VISION.

32:07.767 --> 32:09.067
YOU SHOULD MAKE IT
SO YOU CAN'T SEE

32:09.100 --> 32:10.733
WHAT'S GOING ON DOWN THERE.

32:12.733 --> 32:14.100
YEAH,
MY FAVORITE PART.

32:14.133 --> 32:17.733
MATT: Hello. Hello. Edgar, Jake,
you guys still up there?

32:17.767 --> 32:19.600
Narrator: BEFORE EDGAR
CAN GET THE TOUR...

32:19.633 --> 32:21.133
Hello. Hello. Hello.

32:21.167 --> 32:25.967
...A CALL COMES IN FROM HIS
COWORKER, DECKHAND MATT BRADLEY.

32:26.067 --> 32:28.900
YOU GOT ME HERE, MATT.
WHAT'S GOING ON?

32:28.933 --> 32:30.367
They're running an EKG.

32:30.400 --> 32:32.933
They said they had
sent results to Seattle.

32:32.967 --> 32:38.067
One said yes,
the other said no on an EKG.

32:41.533 --> 32:45.733
They don't want
to take any chances.

32:45.767 --> 32:48.400
Sig needs to go to Anchorage.

32:48.433 --> 32:51.700
They'll probably
medevac him out.

32:51.733 --> 32:54.067
MM, DOESN'T SOUND
GOOD AT ALL.

32:54.100 --> 32:58.067
Hey, Edgar, I can come grab you
in the truck right now.

32:58.067 --> 33:00.733
YEAH, GO FOR IT.

33:00.767 --> 33:01.967
All right,
let me put my boots on.

33:02.067 --> 33:03.667
I'm on on my way, brother.

33:03.700 --> 33:06.367
**

33:06.400 --> 33:08.600
[BLEEP]

33:08.633 --> 33:11.433
**

33:11.467 --> 33:15.800
WORST-CASE SCENARIO.
WORST-CASE SCENARIO.

33:23.067 --> 33:26.633
CRAPPY, BAD VISIBILITY,
BIG WAVES,

33:26.667 --> 33:28.400
I THINK I CAN
HONESTLY SAY NOW

33:28.433 --> 33:29.767
THAT THIS HAS BEEN
THE WORST WEATHER

33:29.800 --> 33:33.233
WE'VE HAD PROBABLY A DECADE.

33:33.267 --> 33:34.633
HEADS UP!
HEADS UP!

33:34.667 --> 33:38.067
Narrator: THE 2017 OPIE SEASON
IS SHAPING UP TO BE

33:38.100 --> 33:40.667
ONE OF THE WORST ON RECORD.

33:40.700 --> 33:44.400
**

33:44.433 --> 33:49.067
Sig: OH, MAN, THESE WAVES
ARE GETTING BIG!

33:49.100 --> 33:51.333
Narrator: AND IT'S NOT OVER YET.

33:51.367 --> 33:53.933
WATCH OUT!

33:53.967 --> 33:57.400
**

33:57.433 --> 33:58.933
NAMASTE.

33:58.967 --> 34:01.633
UH-OH.

34:01.667 --> 34:05.167
Narrator: THE TIME BANDIT
STAYS HOT IN THE RUSSIAN COLD,

34:05.200 --> 34:09.100
BUT THE WIZARD STORMS
ITS WAY TO SECOND PLACE.

34:12.300 --> 34:17.167
Narrator: 295 MILES
NORTHWEST OF DUTCH HARBOR

34:17.199 --> 34:19.067
ON THE WIZARD...

34:19.100 --> 34:22.567
I WOULDN'T SAY THAT WE FISHED
THROUGH THE STORM.

34:22.600 --> 34:25.500
WE WORKED IN THE STORM.

34:25.533 --> 34:29.100
Narrator: ...AFTER RESETTING
IN A VICIOUS 65-KNOT STORM,

34:29.132 --> 34:33.067
CAPTAIN KEITH COLBURN
IS READY TO REAP THE REWARDS.

34:33.067 --> 34:35.500
START WITH A BANG,
THAT'S WHAT WE NEED.

34:35.533 --> 34:36.967
WE'VE GOT ONE TIME
THROUGH THE GEAR,

34:37.067 --> 34:39.167
AND THEN WE HEAD
TO TOWN TO DELIVER.

34:39.199 --> 34:42.967
SO, WE REALLY NEED
THIS STORM SET TO PAY OFF.

34:43.067 --> 34:45.533
Narrator:
IF HIS RESET FAILS TO HIT,

34:45.567 --> 34:48.567
THE VETERAN SKIPPER
WILL BE FORCED TO GO IN LATE.

34:48.600 --> 34:53.567
I GOT HIGH HOPES THAT HOPEFULLY
ON ABOUT A 250 AVERAGE.

34:53.600 --> 34:56.766
**

34:56.800 --> 34:59.633
OKAY, THIS FIRST ONE'S
COMING UP.

34:59.667 --> 35:03.400
**

35:03.433 --> 35:06.100
YOU KNOW, WE'RE JUST PICKING
A FEW CRAB IN OUR POTS,

35:06.133 --> 35:07.833
BUT WE'RE HOPING THAT THE POTS

35:07.867 --> 35:11.800
THAT WE SET BACK
ARE GOING TO HAVE SOME.

35:11.833 --> 35:16.833
Keith:
HOPEFULLY, WE DIDN'T JUST DO A
STORM SET AND GET NOTHING HERE.

35:16.867 --> 35:20.267
AT THIS POINT, THERE'S NOWHERE
FOR US TO RUN AND COVER.

35:20.300 --> 35:23.333
**

35:27.667 --> 35:29.267
COME ON, CRAB.

35:29.300 --> 35:30.267
COME ON, CRAB.

35:30.300 --> 35:32.667
YEAH, BABY!
WHOO-HOO!

35:32.700 --> 35:34.767
OH, YEAH, YOU CAN SEE
THE CRAB FROM HERE.

35:34.800 --> 35:37.200
[ ALL CHEERING ]

35:37.233 --> 35:38.900
THIS POT IS
A NICE-LOOKING POT, MAN.

35:41.067 --> 35:43.267
WE JUST NEEDS SOME POTS
THAT POP. THAT'S IT. JUST A FEW.

35:43.300 --> 35:46.400
LET'S STUFF THESE TANKS
REAL QUICK.

35:46.433 --> 35:49.200
TWO EIGHT ZERO.

35:49.233 --> 35:50.867
280.

35:50.900 --> 35:52.733
NOW, THAT'S GOOD NEWS.

35:52.767 --> 35:54.100
THE FACT THAT WE'RE PUTTING
SOMETHING IN THE TANKS

35:54.133 --> 35:55.433
IS A BIG PLUS.

35:55.467 --> 35:57.167
**

35:57.200 --> 35:58.800
YEAH!

35:58.833 --> 36:01.833
[ ALL CHEERING ]

36:01.867 --> 36:03.500
IT'S PICKING UP, THOUGH.
LOOK RIGHT THERE.

36:06.967 --> 36:10.600
THE SOUND OF THE HOPPER SHAKING
IS MUSIC TO MY EARS.

36:10.633 --> 36:13.067
[ IMITATES SHAKING ]

36:13.067 --> 36:15.133
PROBABLY 700 CRAB IN THAT POT.

36:15.167 --> 36:17.867
200 TO 300 OF THEM
ARE GOING IN THE TANK.

36:17.900 --> 36:20.467
IT'S BEEN BLOWING FOR DAYS NOW.

36:20.500 --> 36:24.267
FEEL LIKE WE HAVEN'T HAD
A SOLID FOOTING IN A WHILE.

36:24.300 --> 36:27.400
BUT THE GOOD NEWS IS
CATCHING CRAB.

36:27.433 --> 36:29.867
WE'RE MOVING.
THE SPIRITS ARE HIGH.

36:29.900 --> 36:31.733
Three two five.

36:31.767 --> 36:35.300
RIGHT ON. 325. PERFECT.

36:35.333 --> 36:38.333
**

36:38.367 --> 36:41.633
WHOO-HOO!

36:43.667 --> 36:45.733
THIS IS GOOD NEWS RIGHT HERE
BECAUSE THIS IS RIGHT

36:45.767 --> 36:47.100
WHERE WE GOT
ALL OF OUR GEAR,

36:47.133 --> 36:51.100
AND WE'RE GETTING NICE,
FULL POTS OF CRAB.

36:51.133 --> 36:53.333
[ ALL CHEERING ]

36:53.367 --> 36:56.067
**

36:56.100 --> 36:57.300
HEY, YOU KNOW WHAT?

36:57.333 --> 36:58.733
GO AHEAD AND DUMP
THAT POT FOR TOWN.

36:58.767 --> 37:00.300
HEY! WHOO!

37:00.333 --> 37:02.367
YEAH!

37:02.400 --> 37:04.933
-YEAH, BABY!
-WHOO!

37:04.967 --> 37:08.933
WORKING THROUGH THAT STORM
HAS PAID HUGE DIVIDENDS.

37:08.967 --> 37:10.567
THAT'S WHAT MATTERS.

37:10.600 --> 37:13.667
**

37:13.700 --> 37:16.933
WE'RE GOING TO GET OUR GEAR SET

37:16.967 --> 37:18.567
AND ANOTHER HALF A DAY'S
WORTH OF WORK IN

37:18.600 --> 37:20.200
WHILE THESE GUYS
ARE ALL ANCHORED UP

37:20.233 --> 37:21.733
OR TRAVELING OR JOGGING.

37:21.767 --> 37:25.500
**

37:25.533 --> 37:28.433
GOOD DEAL, MAN. THIS HAS TURNED
INTO A GOOD TRIP FOR US.

37:28.467 --> 37:30.333
[ ALL CHEERING ]

37:30.367 --> 37:33.400
**

37:35.733 --> 37:38.767
Narrator: 90 MILES NORTHEAST...

37:38.800 --> 37:39.800
Man: YEP!

37:39.833 --> 37:41.833
...ON ST. PAUL ISLAND...

37:41.867 --> 37:44.600
-THAT'S BRAILER!
-THAT'S BRAILER!

37:44.633 --> 37:46.900
Man: COMING UP, OPIES!

37:46.933 --> 37:49.233
JAKE WILL GET THE FINAL NUMBER.

37:49.267 --> 37:51.467
I'M MAKING IT HAPPEN
WITH FOUR GUYS.

37:51.500 --> 37:53.267
Narrator: ...AS THE CREW OF
THE SAGA FINISH UP

37:53.300 --> 37:57.067
THE LAST OF
A 30,000-POUND OFF-LOAD...

37:57.100 --> 37:58.867
DEAN.

37:58.900 --> 38:02.200
...CAPTAIN JAKE ANDERSON HAS
ONE MORE PIECE OF BUSINESS

38:02.233 --> 38:05.700
TO ATTEND TO
BEFORE THROWING LINES.

38:08.367 --> 38:12.500
IT'S NOT VERY EASY
MAKING THIS DECISION.

38:12.533 --> 38:16.600
I SAY A LOT OF [BLEEP]
WHEN I'M ANGRY,

38:16.633 --> 38:20.533
AND YOU'RE A GOOD HAND.

38:20.567 --> 38:24.600
AND I LIKE THE WORK THAT YOU DO
WHEN YOU DO WORK,

38:24.633 --> 38:28.900
AND TODAY, YOU
[BLEEP] SAVED US BIG TIME.

38:31.833 --> 38:34.867
YEAH.

38:34.900 --> 38:36.733
WE'RE GOING TO DROP YOU OFF,
GOING TO MAKE SURE

38:36.767 --> 38:40.300
YOU'RE PAID
FOR YOUR TIME SERVED.

38:40.333 --> 38:43.200
YEAH.
NO, THAT'S FINE.

38:43.233 --> 38:45.667
ARE YOU GOING TO GO BACK OUT
WITH FOUR GUYS?

38:45.700 --> 38:48.333
YEAH.
I'LL DEAL WITH IT.

38:48.367 --> 38:51.467
YEP.

38:51.500 --> 38:54.933
Narrator: ...AFTER WEIGHING
THE PROS AND CONS...

38:54.967 --> 38:57.900
Man: HEY, YOU WANT TO
THROW THESE UP THERE?

38:57.933 --> 39:00.700
Jake: I'M READY TO GO
WHEN YOU GUYS ARE.

39:00.733 --> 39:04.467
Narrator:
...THE YOUNG SKIPPER SENDS
HIS SENIOR DECKHAND PACKING.

39:04.500 --> 39:06.767
WE'RE GETTING OUT OF HERE.

39:06.800 --> 39:08.467
Jake: HOPEFULLY,
ALL THOSE PROBLEMS

39:08.500 --> 39:12.067
THAT WENT WITH DEAN
ARE GONE, TOO,

39:12.067 --> 39:15.867
BUT...WE'LL SEE.

39:15.900 --> 39:18.933
**

39:27.567 --> 39:32.267
Narrator: JUST A FEW MILES
DOWN THE ROAD...

39:32.300 --> 39:36.567
[ SIGHS ]
HERE WE GO AGAIN.

39:36.600 --> 39:39.533
THIS IS SUCH A [BLEEP]

39:39.567 --> 39:40.833
I KNEW IF I WALKED
IN THAT CLINIC,

39:40.867 --> 39:42.200
I WAS GOING TO
[BLEEP] MYSELF.

39:42.233 --> 39:44.500
YEAH.

39:44.533 --> 39:46.900
YOU CAN'T TAKE ANY CHANCES AFTER
WHAT YOU WENT THROUGH.

39:46.933 --> 39:48.600
IF IT LOOKS LIKE I CAN
GET OUT OF THERE,

39:48.633 --> 39:50.433
THEN WE'LL MAKE A PLAN.
YEAH.

39:50.467 --> 39:54.467
**

39:54.500 --> 39:55.733
BE BACK.

39:55.767 --> 39:57.400
ALL RIGHT,
NO PROBLEM.

39:57.433 --> 40:00.467
**

40:02.533 --> 40:05.333
ALL RIGHT,
GUYS, FLY SAFE.

40:05.367 --> 40:07.700
Edgar: SO, YEAH,
I'LL HEAD BACK TO THE BOAT.

40:07.733 --> 40:09.367
I'LL GET WORD
FIRST THING IN THE MORNING

40:09.400 --> 40:11.267
WHENEVER
HE GETS RESULTS.

40:11.300 --> 40:12.900
AT LEAST, THAT'S THE PLAN.

40:12.933 --> 40:15.967
**

40:18.767 --> 40:20.900
I'M WORRIED ABOUT HIM.

40:20.933 --> 40:24.667
I KNOW I'M SCARED THAT IT COULD
ESCALATE AND GET WORSE.

40:24.700 --> 40:26.833
YOU KNOW, WE'RE ALL
IN THIS TOGETHER.

40:26.867 --> 40:29.933
I MEAN, WE KNEW
THAT THERE WAS A CHANCE.

40:29.967 --> 40:32.033
IT JUST SUCKS
WHEN IT'S YOUR FAMILY.

40:32.067 --> 40:35.100
**

40:44.200 --> 40:45.933
Narrator: STILL TO COME...

40:45.967 --> 40:48.267
Man: YEAH!

40:48.300 --> 40:50.267
Narrator: ...ON THIS SEASON
OF "DEADLIEST CATCH"...

40:50.300 --> 40:53.800
Jake: THE BERING SEA IS
A TAKER OF LIVES.

40:53.833 --> 40:57.100
SHE WILL EXPLOIT
YOUR EVERY WEAKNESS.

40:57.133 --> 40:59.233
**

40:59.267 --> 41:01.900
Man:
OKAY! WATCH OUT!

41:01.933 --> 41:05.967
-WATCH THAT BLOCK!
-[ BLEEP ].

41:06.067 --> 41:07.733
Man:
THERE'S A 75-CLIP VESSEL

41:07.767 --> 41:10.367
WITH THREE PEOPLE ONBOARD
THAT RAN AGROUND.

41:10.400 --> 41:12.767
Edgar: I WANT SIG TO KNOW
THAT IF THE TIME COMES,

41:12.800 --> 41:15.067
THEN HE'S GOT SOMEBODY
RESPONSIBLE ENOUGH

41:15.100 --> 41:17.233
TO BE ABLE TO TAKE OVER.

41:17.267 --> 41:19.467
Man:
HAPPY RETIREMENT, HILLSTRAND!

41:19.500 --> 41:22.067
[ ALL CHEERING ]

41:22.067 --> 41:23.733
I DON'T BELIEVE THIS IS REAL.

